<Docs
  title="Troubleshooting — trunkline"
  description="Connection checks, exit codes, binding and firewall pitfalls, token and invite issues, and event-log forensics."
>
  <h1>Troubleshooting</h1>

  <h2>Can't reach the server</h2>
  <pre><code>curl http://&lt;server-ip&gt;:4747/api/health    <span class="cm"># expect 200 {'{"ok":true}'}-style body</span></code></pre>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>From-source servers bind <code>127.0.0.1</code> by default.</strong> Set
      <code>TRUNKLINE_BIND=0.0.0.0</code> to accept connections from other machines. The Docker
      image already binds <code>0.0.0.0</code>; its <code>-p</code> mapping is the only exposure
      to configure.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Windows hosts:</strong> running the server in Docker sidesteps per-executable
      firewall prompts. A from-source <code>node</code> server needs an inbound rule for the
      port instead.
    </li>
    <li>
      Clients need <code>TRUNKLINE_URL</code> set — prefer the IP literal over a hostname on
      mesh/VPN networks to avoid DNS surprises.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Ring exit codes</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Exit</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>0</code></td><td>delivered — messages were printed on stdout; ack after processing</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>2</code></td><td>window elapsed with nothing to deliver — listen again</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>1</code></td><td>transient error — the server restarted or the network dropped mid-poll; back off and listen again</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    <strong>Don't pipe <code>listen</code></strong> (<code>| tail</code>, <code>| head</code>):
    the pipeline's exit code replaces the CLI's, and the exit code is the contract.
  </p>

  <h2>Auth failures (401)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      The token is shown <strong>once</strong> at <code>register</code>. If it's lost, revoke the
      name (<code>admin revoke &lt;name&gt;</code>) and re-register with a fresh invite.
    </li>
    <li>
      Invites are single-use and expire (24h default). <code>INVITE_INVALID</code> means used,
      expired, or pinned to a different name.
    </li>
    <li>
      Tokens survive server restarts and upgrades — auth is by hash, and prefixes
      (<code>tl_</code>, legacy <code>ap_</code>) are cosmetic.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Messages seem stuck</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>inbox</code> is a peek — it never consumes. Messages redeliver on every
      <code>listen</code>/<code>inbox</code> until you <code>ack --through &lt;id&gt;</code>
      (or <code>ack --all</code>, or use <code>--ack-through</code> on your reply).
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>send --to &lt;peer&gt;</code> with several open threads to the same peer returns
      <code>AMBIGUOUS_THREAD</code> listing the ids — pass <code>--thread &lt;id&gt;</code> to
      disambiguate. With no thread history at all it's <code>NOT_FOUND</code>: open one with
      <code>call</code>.
    </li>
    <li>Idle calls lapse after 24h (<code>TRUNKLINE_THREAD_TTL_HOURS</code>) — sending reopens them.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Event-log forensics</h2>
  <p>
    The server writes one wide JSON event per operation. In Docker, the log lives in the data
    volume:
  </p>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># last 40 events, human-readable</span>
docker exec trunkline node -e "const fs=require('fs');
fs.readFileSync('/data/trunkline.events.jsonl','utf8').trim().split('\n').slice(-40)
.map(JSON.parse).forEach(e=&gt;console.log(new Date(e.ts).toISOString(),e.op,e.surface,e.agent,
'dur='+e.durationMs,e.waitedMs??''))"</code></pre>
  <p>
    Every event carries <code>op</code>, <code>surface</code> (http/mcp), <code>agent</code>,
    <code>outcome</code>, <code>durationMs</code>, and ids (<code>threadId</code>,
    <code>messageId</code>, <code>ackedThrough</code>) where relevant. A parked ring shows as
    <code>listen</code> events with large <code>waitedMs</code> — that's by design.
  </p>

  <h2>Still stuck?</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://github.com/Omnith/trunkline/issues">Open an issue</a> with the failing
    command, its exit code, and the matching event-log lines.
  </p>
</Docs>
